------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 


<H5>  VI. Foreign Trade and International Tourism </H5>
  Foreign trade developed further, although the export growth 
rate dropped. The 1993 total export and import value for the 
province was $1.925 billion, up 16.8 percent from the previous 
year on a comparable basis. Of this total, total export value 
was $1.366 billion, up 4.9 percent. Industrial and mining 
products accounted for 66.4 percent of the total export value, 
an increase of 2.1 percentage points from the previous year. 
  New levels were attained in the utilization of foreign 
capital. In 1993, 1,672 units across the province signed new 
agreements, 58.3 percent more than the previous year. 
Agreements on the utilization of foreign capital amounted to 
$2.195 billion, up 108 percent. Foreign capital actually 
utilized was $692 million, up 161 percent. Of this, $467 million 
-- 337 percent -- was in the form of direct investment by guest 
companies, the highest level so far of the province's actual 
utilization of foreign capital. Port construction increased in 
pace and investment environment was further improved. 
  Economic and technological cooperation with other countries 
made new progress. The province contracted 67 projects and 
labor service in 1993 with foreign countries, worth $87.06 
million in contract money. The completed annual operation 
revenue was $73.13 million, up 132 percent from the previous 
year. 
  International tourism developed faster. In 1993 the province 
received 129,400 tourists staying overnight, up 17.5 percent 
over the previous year. Foreign exchange earnings from tourism 
amounted to 88.53 million yuan (in foreign exchange 
certificates), up 7.7 percent. Of that, earnings from commodity 
sales was 4.78 million yuan, down 1.9 percent. 
<H5>  VII. Banking and Insurance </H5>
  In 1993, the province's banking sector conscientiously 
implemented the central authorities' spirit of strengthening and 
improving macroregulation and control, carried a sound and 
steady monetary policy, corrected problems in banking work, 
vigorously raised capital, and adjusted its credit structure, 
which effectively supported the sustained, rapid, and healthy 
development of the province's economy. At the end of 1993, the 
savings deposits of all the province's banks was 114.388 billion 
yuan, an increase of 20.715 billion yuan over the figure at the 
beginning of the year. The balance of all loans was 137.205 
billion yuan, 23.536 billion yuan more than at the beginning of 
the year. The net amount of money supplied for the whole year 
was 6.409 billion yuan, down 7.9 percent from the previous year. 
  The savings deposits of urban and rural residents increased 
steadily. At the end of 1993, the balance of the savings 
deposits of all urban and rural residents was 76.717 billion 
yuan, an increase of 17.184 billion yuan over the figure at the 
beginning of the year, up 28.9 percent. 
  Further development was made in insurance. The premiums for 
all kinds of property insurance in 1993 totalled 179.3 billion 
yuan, up 23.5 percent from the previous year. Across the 
province, 16,594 enterprises participated in enterprise property 
insurance schemes; 800,700 households in family property 
insurance schemes; and 17,258,400 people participated in life 
insurance. Insurance companies handled 596,200 cases of claims 
of property loss and paid an indemnity of 760 million yuan and 
35,000 persons were paid 220 million yuan as damages in life 
insurance. 
<H5>  VIII. Science and Technology, Education, Culture, Public </H5>
Health, and Sports 
  Scientific and technological research made new progress. The 
rate at which scientific and technological research results 
being transformed into actual productive forces increased. In 
1993, 30 scientific and technological results won prizes from 
the state, of which three won state invention prizes, 22 won 
state scientific and technological progress prizes, and five 
state Spark prizes; 310 won the province government's scientific 
and technological progress prize, and 87 won the Spark prize. 
Soft sciences also achieved research results. New ground was 
broken in technological development and high-tech industry. In 
1993, 80 percent of the province's key scientific and 
technological research results were applied and popularized. 
The scientific and technological management and service system 
in rural areas were further improved. The "Spark Plan" played a 
positive role in sustaining the invigoration of the rural 
economy. 
  Technological markets continued to be active. The province 
signed 17,140 contracts on various technologies, 2,500 more than 
the previous year. The contract signed involved a transaction 
value of 901 million yuan. The province applied to the state a 
total of 2,299 patents in 1993, 301 more than the previous year; 
and authorized 1,669 patents, 940 more; and 23 percent of the 
province's patented technology found its way into production. 
  Scientific and technological backup services were steadily 
expanded. By the end of 1993, there were 6,717 technological 
and supervisory professionals actively drafting and revising 
provincial rules and regulations on technology. Cartographical 
sections drew 8,000 maps in various scales and published 16 
kinds of maps. Meteorological and seismological technical 
services made new progress to keep in step with the province's 
social and economic development. 
  The province's scientific and technological force continued 
to expand. At the end of 1993, state-owned enterprises across 
the province employed 878,000 technical professionals, 60,000 
more than the previous year. Of the scientific and 
technological personnel, those middle ranking or above numbered 
264,000, 66,000 more than the previous year. 
  Education developed steadily. In 1993, ordinary institutes 
of higher learning of the whole province enrolled 40,500 
students of general and special studies and 104,400 full-time 
on-campus students; and overall, there were 26,700 students 
graduated from these institutes. Such institutes and research 
units enrolled 386 graduate students, had 1,047 students 
pursuing graduate courses, and saw 338 complete their graduate 
studies. To meet the demand of the labor market, there was 
adjustment in the structure of higher education, and such 
adjustment scored results, with the ratios between the number 
and kind of courses and special studies better rationalized. 
The secondary education structure was increasingly 
rationalized. In 1993, ordinary technical secondary schools of 
the whole province had 163,900 on-campus students, 14,900 more 
than the previous year; agricultural (vocational) schools had 
258,600 on-campus students, 54,600 more than the previous year; 
and technical schools had 73,100 on-campus students. There were 
435,200 ordinary senior secondary school students. Basic 
education was continuously strengthened and the nine-year 
compulsory education program made new steps. In 1993, ordinary 
junior secondary schools of the whole province had 3,194,400 
students, and there were 9,515,000 on-campus primary school 
students. 98.9 percent of all the school-age children in the 
province were at school. The kindergartens had 1,834,800 
students. Adult education focused on job training and technical 
education continued to score new results. 
  Cultural undertakings developed healthily. Mass cultural 
activity continued to be active. Cultural activity with local 
characteristics was launched extensively. Province-wide there 
were 18 broadcasting stations and 17 television stations 
producing in 1993 a total of 70 television dramas. The 
provincial radio and television broadcasting covered 89 percent 
and 81 percent respectively of the province's population. In 
1993, the province published 2,313 kinds of books and 
pictorials, printed 918 million copies of newspapers, and 
published 104.9 million copies of various magazines. 
  Public health and medical conditions continued to improve. 
Year-end hospital beds for the whole province numbered 172,200, 
up 1.6 percent from the previous year. Professional medical 
staff numbered 298,400, up 3.1 percent. Of this number, there 
were 101,600 doctors, 2,600 more than the previous year; and 
52,500 nurses, an increase of 1,800. Prevention and medical 
care continued to be strengthened. In 1993, there were 193 
medical and epidemic prevention organs in the whole province, 
two more than the previous year; and 14,038 people working 
professionally for epidemic prevention, an increase of 1,039. 
Medical conditions in rural areas continued to improve. 
Medical stations spread across the rural areas of the province. 
The overall standard of medical care and services, however, 
remain to be raised. 
  Notable headway was made in sport. Athletes from our 
province won 39 gold, 22 silver, and 19 bronze medals in major 
domestic and international sport competitions. At the 7th 
National Sports Meet, our athletes won 20.5 gold, nine silver, 
and 18 bronze medals, and our province ranked 10th nationally on 
overall team scores and 6th in the number of gold medals won, 
taking our province's sports to the forefront of national sport. 
Sports among the people were pursued actively. 
<H5>  IX. Population and People's Livelihood </H5>
  Family planning made fresh achievements. According to a 
sampling survey on changes in the province's population, the 
birth rate of the population was 15.87 per thousand, the death 
rate was 6.35 per thousand, and the natural population growth 
rate was 9.52 per thousand, down 1.62 per thousand from the 
previous year. Calculated on this basis, the province's total 
year-end population in 1993 was 89.46 million, an increase of 
850,000 people. 
  Urban and rural residents' income increased and their living 
standards rose. In 1993, the total payroll of the whole 
province was 19.164 billion yuan, up 15.8 percent from the 
previous year. The per capita pay for the entire work force was 
2,557 yuan, up 12.7 percent. A sampling survey shows that in 
1993, the per capita subsistence income for urban and rural 
residents was 1,792.88 yuan, up 22.9 percent from the previous 
year, or 11.1 percent after allowing for price increases. The 
per capita living expenditure was 1,069.24 yuan, up 19.9 
percent, or 8.4 percent after allowing for price increases. In 
1993, the per capita net income of the entire rural population 
was 696.85 yuan, up 18.2 percent from the previous year, or 9 
percent after allowing for price increases; the per capita 
living expenditure was 564.93 yuan, up 19.5 percent or 8.4 
percent after allowing for price increases. Urban and rural 
residents' income rose further, but income disparity widened, 
and the actual consumption of some low-income families went down. 
  Reforms in the labor and personnel system continued to 
deepen. In 1993 the province found jobs for 243,900 job-waiting 
people in townships and towns. By the end of the year, there 
were 7,526,900 workers, an increase of 64,500 people from the 
previous year. Of this total, state-owned units employed 
5,778,200 and collective units 1,706,500. There were 1,636,400 
contract workers at state-owned units, accounting for 28.3 
percent of total workers employed by state-owned units, a rise 
of three percentage points from the previous year. Units of all 
other ownerships employed 42,200 people, an increase of 17,000 
people. The labor market continued to be active, a talent 
market was forming, and talent mobility was becoming 
rationalized, standardized, and institutionalized. 
  Living conditions for urban and rural residents improved. In 
1993, a total of 11,712,200 square meters of new residential 
buildings were completed in urban areas and 32.45 million square 
meters in rural areas. Per capita living space for all whole 
urban residents at year's end was 11.53 square meters, up 0.33 
square meters at the end of the previous year; that for all 
rural residents was 18.27 square meters, an increase of 1.13 
square meters. 
  The social welfare scheme continuously improved. In 1993, 
there were 2,484 various social welfare institutions across the 
province, sheltering 39,200 people. 7.51 million people in 
urban and rural areas received the benefits of social welfare. 
76 percent of towns and townships established rural socialized 
welfare networks. The coverage of social old-age pensions 
provided by enterprises continued to expand. Urban socialized 
service networks also developed more quickly, with 4,966 
community service facilities established. 
  Note: The GDP figures and growth value figures in various 
sectors in this statistical communique are calculated at current 
prices; whereas growth rates are calculated on comparable prices. 

</TEXT>

