<H5>  VI. Science, Education, Culture, Public Health, and </H5>
Physical Culture 
  With in-depth reforms of the scientific and technological 
system, scientific and technological undertakings further 
developed. In 1993, the region made a total of 257 significant 
scientific and technological achievements above the provincial 
or ministerial level, won one State Science and Technology 
Progress award, and one State Spark award. The region accepted 
214 patent applications, and was authorized 168 patents, an 
increase of 23.7 percent and 84.6 percent respectively over 
1992. The ranks of scientific and technological workers grew. 
In 1993, local state-owned enterprises and public undertakings 
had a total of 120,000 various kinds of technicians, an increase 
of 1.8 percent over those at the end of the previous year. The 
region had 56 state-owned scientific research and development 
organizations at the county level and above, with 5,504 people 
engaged in scientific and technological activities, and four 
information and documents organizations, with 139 people engaged 
in scientific and technological activities. 
  In 1993 the region had a total of 20 product quality 
inspection organizations, and built five super short-wave 
emitting stations for a weather warning and service system. 
  Educational undertakings achieved new results and 
development 
of higher education quickened. The region enrolled nine 
postgraduates, with a total of 26 graduate students in 
universities and colleges. General institutions of higher 
learning enrolled 3,378 undergraduates and students in 
specialized subjects, an increase of 24 percent over the 
previous year, with a total of 9,604 students in universities 
and colleges, 1,129 students more than the previous year. In 
1993 there were 36,193 students in various kinds of secondary 
occupational technical schools (including 12,909 students in 
skilled worker schools). The region had 51,000 senior middle 
school students, 217,000 junior middle school students, and 
628,000 pupils in primary schools. The rate of school age 
children entering schools was 95.2 percent, and the rate of 
primary school graduates entering schools of a higher grade was 
83.1 percent. The conditions for running primary and secondary 
schools were further improved, and dangerous classrooms in rural 
areas were basically rebuilt. 
  In 1993, adult institutions of higher learning enrolled a 
total of 2,746 undergraduates and students in specialized 
subjects, with a total of 6,166 students in universities and 
colleges, an increase of 19 percent over the previous year. 
There were 6,409 students in adult secondary specialized 
schools. Amateur education was strengthened, and a total of 
48,840 persons learned to read and write in 1993. 
  Cultural undertakings. The whole region had a total of 16 
art performance troupes, 22 cultural halls, 20 public libraries, 
three museums, and 32 archives. It had nine broadcasting 
stations, four shortwave broadcasting stations and relay 
stations, five TV stations, and 10 TV emitting and relay 
stations above one kilowatt. The region had 548 various kinds of 
film projecting units, and in 1993 distributed 180 various kinds 
of new films, and made two TV operas in four volumes. In the 
whole year, the region published 45.74 million copies of 
newspapers, 2.276 million copies of magazines, and 16.22 million 
copies of books. 
  Public health undertakings. In 1993, the region had a 
total of 13,000 hospital beds, an increase of 8.3 percent over 
the previous year. It had 21,000 public health workers, an 
increase of 2 percent. Among them were 10,000 doctors, an 
increase of 2.1 percent. There were 42.7 doctors for every 
10,000 people. 
  Physical cultural undertakings. In 1993 the region's 
athletes took part in various kinds of competitions at various 
levels in China, and won two gold medals, five silver medals, 
and four bronze medals. Twenty-two athletes broke 28 regional 
records. Mass sports further developed, and 39 percent of the 
students were up to qualified standards of the "State Physical 
Training Standards." 
<H5>  VII. Population and Life of the People </H5>
  Family planning work was further strengthened, and the 
population growth rate was brought under control. According to 
a sample survey of population in the whole region in 1993, the 
birth rate was 19.43 per thousand, dropping by 0.68 per thousand 
from 1992; mortality was 5.36 per thousand, even with that of 
the previous year; the natural growth rate was 14.07 per 
thousand, dropping by 0.68 per thousand. Based on such 
calculations, the region's total population at the end of 1993 
reached 4.953 million, an increase of 81,000 people over those 
of the previous year, up by 1.66 percent, in which the 
population of the Hui nationality totalled 1.642 million, an 
increase of 2.2 percent. 
  With economic and social development, the income of urban 
and 
rural residents increased, and the quality of life was further 
improved. According to a sample survey, per capita living-cost 
income in cities and towns in 1993 was 1,907 yuan, an increase 
of 304 yuan over the previous year, up 19 percent. With price 
factors deducted, actual growth was 3.3 percent. The net income 
of rural residents amounted to 667 yuan, an increase of 48 yuan 
over the previous year, up 7.8 percent. With prices factor 
deducted, it was even with the previous year. Per capita income 
in plain areas amounted to 886 yuan, an increase of 43.7 yuan 
over the previous year, and per capita income in mountain areas 
(not including Yanchi, which is a hilly area) amounted to 428.7 
yuan, an increase of 72.9 yuan. There were still a number of 
residents in mountain areas whose living standards were quite 
low. 
  Labor structural reforms achieved remarkable success. The 
labor employment service system was further improved. In 1993 
cities and towns in the whole region arranged employment for 
26,600 people, and the wait-for-employment rate in cities and 
towns at the end of the year was 3.7 percent, dropping by 0.4 
percentage points. The whole region had a total of 724,000 
staff and workers at the end of the year, an increase of 5,700 
over the previous year, up 0.79 percent. Among them, staff and 
workers of state-owned units totalled 609,000, and those of 
collective units totalled 112,000 people. The labor contract 
system was further developed, and there were 100,000 staff and 
workers of state-owned units in the region working on a contract 
basis, which accounted for 16.4 percent of staff and workers of 
state-owned units. 
  The wage level of staff and workers was raised. In 1993, 
gross wages of staff and workers in the region totalled 2.15 
billion yuan, an increase of 10.9 percent over 1992, and the 
average wage of staff and workers was 3,015 yuan, an increase of 
341 yuan, up 12.7 percent. 
  Savings of urban and rural residents continued to increase. 
While the consumption level was raised, and stocks, bonds, 
fundraising, and other monetary assets were increased, savings 
deposits of urban and rural residents in the region amounted to 
6.14 billion yuan at the end of 1993, an increase of 22 percent, 
of which the savings of city and town residents totalled 5.27 
billion yuan, up 23.4 percent; and the savings of rural 
residents totalled 870 million yuan, up 14 percent. 
  The insurance business made great development. In 1993 the 
cumulative total of various kinds of property insurance amounted 
to 19.76 billion yuan, an increase of 7.7 percent over the 
previous year. In the whole region, 2,187 enterprises were 
covered in property insurance, with an insurance amount of 8.2 
billion yuan. Covered in family property insurance were 175,000 
resident families, with an insurance amount of 8.24 billion 
yuan. 974,000 residents carried personal insurance, with an 
insurance amount of 4.08 billion yuan. A total of 14,500 cases 
of domestic property claims were handled by insurance companies, 
with a payment of 30.58 million yuan of indemnity, and 4.25 
million yuan of indemnity were paid to 7,335 residents for 
personal insurance. 
  Living conditions in urban and rural areas were further 
improved. According to a sample survey, per capita living space 
in cities and towns in 1993 was 11.1 square meters, and per 
capita living space in rural areas was 15.4 square meters. 
  Social welfare undertakings. In 1993 various social welfare 
institutions in the whole region had a total of 457 beds, which 
took in 387 people. For various kinds of people who needed 
social relief, 900,000 person times got relief, and various 
kinds of community service facilities were further improved. 
  Environmental protection undertakings. In 1993 there were 
altogether 607 staff and workers in the region's environmental 
protection departments and affiliated organizations which had 13 
environmental monitoring stations at various levels, and 54 
projects were completed against pollution which must be brought 
under control within the specified time. A total of 48.5 square 
kilometers of dust control areas in cities were built, and 35.6 
square kilometers of areas were built that were up to antinoise 
pollution standards. 
  Note: Gross domestic product (GDP) and total output and 
added values of various industries listed in the communique are 
current price values, and growth rates are calculated by 
comparable prices. 
  Some of the data in the communique contains annual bulletin 
figures. 

</TEXT>

