------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 


  The development of the postal and telecommunications 
services 
maintained a relatively high rate of growth and was the fastest 
for many years. The total output of postal and 
telecommunications services was 710 million yuan, 44.6 percent 
up, of which mobile telephones increased by 180 percent, radio 
paging by 210 percent, and express postal services by 110 
percent. The development of long-distance telephone and urban 
telephone services was further speeded up. Sixty-four cities 
and counties were added to the long-distance telephone service 
network, 82.6 percent up. The net increase in 
program-controlled urban telephones was 234,000 sets and the 
total number of such telephones was 372,000. The proportion of 
program-controlled telephones increased from 60.9 to 87.7 
percent. Although postal and telecommunications services have 
developed quite fast in recent years, they still cannot meet the 
needs of the social and economic development. 
<H5>  V. Domestic Commerce and Market Prices </H5>
  The domestic consumer goods market was brisk. In 1993, 
establishing a new type of property rights system and further 
changing the operational mechanism were regarded as the core of 
the work in the circulation field. Greater efforts were made to 
constantly deepen reform and breakthroughs were achieved in 
developing a circulation pattern which met the needs of the 
market economy. There was an ample supply of commodities in the 
consumer goods market and buying and selling were brisk. The 
total retail sales volume of commodities in society amounted to 
27.24 billion yuan, 14.8 percent up (the actual growth was 2.7 
percent after allowing for price rises). The retail sales 
volume of consumer goods amounted to 24.55 billion yuan, an 
increase of 17.8 percent. The retail sales volume of the means 
of agricultural production amounted to 2.69 billion yuan, down 
7.2 percent. Of the retail sales volume of consumer goods, 
cities and towns accounted for 17.53 billion yuan, an increase 
of 21 percent, and rural areas accounted for 7.02 billion yuan, 
an increase of 10.6 percent. 
  The retail sales volume of commodities of various types in 
the economy grew comprehensively. The volume of state-owned 
units increased by 11.7 percent, that of collective units by 
12.1 percent, that of self-employed businessmen by 16.1 percent, 
and that of peasants to nonagricultural residents by 41.6 
percent. 
  Buying and selling was also brisk in the capital goods 
market. In the first half of last year, because of the shortage 
in resources and the increase in demand, supplies of most 
capital goods were short, their prices increased, and the 
contradiction between supply and demand was conspicuous. In the 
second half of the year, the demand dropped, prices decreased, 
and more were in stock. The purchase volume of capital goods of 
material supply and marketing enterprises amounted to 13.88 
billion yuan, 32.8 percent up; the marketing volume amounted to 
14.29 billion yuan, an increase of 26.1 percent; and the volume 
in stock increased by 24.2 percent. 
  Greater efforts were made in price reform and the situation 
whereby the prices of products from basic industries had been on 
the low side over a long period was changed to a certain extent 
and the price-forming mechanism moved another step toward the 
market. In 1993, the state removed restrictions on the prices 
for rolled steel, removed some restrictions on those for coal, 
and increased the prices of electricity and railway 
transportation. Beginning in April, the province gradually 
removed restrictions on the prices of grain and coal for 
domestic use on the market and increased the prices of chemical 
fertilizer, urban public transport charges, drinking water, the 
means of agricultural production, farmland irrigation, and the 
prices for medical services. The percentage of commodities 
whose prices were fixed by the state was further reduced and the 
price-forming mechanism was obviously improved. As a result of 
the integration of the readjustment, and removal, of 
restrictions on prices in price reform; the rise in the costs of 
production; and market supply and demand, the range of increase 
in market prices was still quite wide despite state 
macroeconomic readjustment and control. In particular, the 
range of the rise in prices in the living expenses of residents 
in large and medium-sized cities was quite wide following the 
rise in the prices or charges for grain, edible oils, rent, 
transport, schooling, and entertainment. 

    Changes in various categories of price indexes in 1993 as 
compared with 1992 are as follows (taking those for 1992 as 100): 


