<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Court Convicts 30 Councilors for Corruption </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Court Convicts 30 Councilors for Corruption </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2506093494 Taipei CNA in English 0641 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2506093494 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Benjamin Yeh] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, June 25 (CNA) -- The Taoyuan District Court 
in northern Taiwan on Friday [24 June] convicted and sentenced 
30 Taoyuan County councilors to up to two years in prison on 
charges of vote-buying and corruption and acquitted two others. 
  Hsu Chen-yun, the speaker of the Taoyuan County Council, 
received a two-year jail term and had his civil rights stripped 
for three years. According to the verdict, Hsu gave money and 
offered sightseeing trips to councilors in exchange for their 
votes in the March 1 county council election. 
  Hsu, a Kuomintang member, had pleaded not guilty to the 
charges. He will appeal. Twenty-nine other councilors who along 
with Hsu were found guilty by the court were given prison terms 
ranging from 10 months to 22 months and all had their civil 
rights suspended for two years. Each had pleaded not guilty. 
  Fourteen of the 29 councilors are KMT members, six are 
affiliated with the Democratic Progressive Party, Taiwan's 
largest opposition party, and nine others are independents. 
  Twenty-nine people in Keelung city as well as Miaoli, 
Kaohsiung and Hualien counties, including a speaker and three 
deputy speakers, had previously been sentenced for either paying 
or accepting bribes. 
  Separately, prosecutors in 10 other cities and counties 
across Taiwan have charged over 350 on similar charges in 
Taiwan's worst election scandal. The Kuomintang won all 23 city 
and council speaker posts in the polls. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

