Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials Concerned Over Growth in Money Supply </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Officials Concerned Over Growth in Money Supply </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2506085494 Taipei CNA in English 0708 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2506085494 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Sofia Wu] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, June 25 (CNA) -- The domestic money supply 
grew at a faster-than-expected pace in May, causing concern 
among senior finance officials. The annual growth rates of the 
three major indices measuring the domestic money supply M1A, M1B 
and M2 reached 11.45 percent, 16.5 percent and 15.73 percent 
respectively in May, all higher than the April levels, according 
to statistics released by the Central Bank of China (CBC) 
Saturday [25 June]. 
  The M1A and M1B growth rates reached three-month highs, 
while 
the broadly-defined M2 growth rate was at its highest level 
since April 1993, when the rate hit 16.5 percent. May's M2 and 
M1B growth rates also exceeded the CBC-set 15 percent ceiling. 
  CBC Governor Liang Kuo-shu said the central bank has begun 
open-market operations to control the growth of domestic money 
supply. "We believe that through our open-market operations, the 
M2 annual growth rate will fall below the 15-percent ceiling in 
June," he said. 
  CBC Deputy Governor Chiu Cheng-hsiung attributed the high 
money supply growth rate for May in part to increased bank loans 
to manufacturers during the month. As local banks still have 
huge excess reserves, Chiu said, the central bank will intensify 
open-market operations to retrieve idle funds from the banking 
system to staunch money-supply growth. "We'll continue 
monitoring the domestic financial situation closely and will 
take necessary steps to keep the M2, M1A, and M1B growth rates 
within 10 to 15 percent," he added. 
  M2 is the broadest measure of a country's total money stock, 
comprising currency in circulation, checking and demand deposits 
as well as quasi-money (including time deposits and Treasury 
bills). The narrowly-defined M1A comprises cash in circulation 
and deposits in demand and checking accounts, while M1B 
comprises M1A plus passbook savings deposits. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

