<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Taipei Leading Beijing in Trade With ASEAN </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Taipei Leading Beijing in Trade With ASEAN </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2706080394 Taipei CNA in English 0718 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2706080394 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Debbie Kuo] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, June 27 (CNA) -- Taiwan's U.S.$2.27 billion 
in exports to Association of Southeast Asian Nations [ASEAN] 
members in the first quarter of the year more than doubled 
Mainland China's exports to those countries, the Council for 
Economic Planning and Development (CEPD) reported Monday [27 
June]. 
  Taiwan also imported about 1.5 times more imports from ASEAN 
as a whole than did Mainland China, purchasing U.S.$1.82 billion 
worth of goods, the latest CEPD tallies show. ASEAN groups 
Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Thailand, and 
Singapore. 
  During the first quarter, Taiwan recorded a trade surplus of 
U.S.$450 million with ASEAN, while Mainland China suffered a 
deficit of U.S.$60 million. Despite the fact that Taiwan had a 
larger amount of two-way trade with ASEAN, Mainland China's 
imports and exports to the region are growing at a faster pace, 
CEPD officials said. 
  Mainland China managed a 46 percent growth in exports to 
ASEAN over the first quarter of 1993 to U.S.$1.14 billion, while 
its imports jumped 35 percent to U.S.$1.2 billion, compared with 
Taiwan's 9.5 percent and 13.5 percent increases, respectively. 
  Singapore remained the major trading partner of both Taiwan 
and Mainland China in the January-March period. Mainland 
China's leading ASEAN trade partners after Singapore were 
Malaysia, Indonesia and the Philippines, in that order, while 
Taiwan's were Thailand, Malaysia, and Indonesia. 

</TEXT>

