<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Bear Li] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, June 24 (CNA) -- The Ministry of Foreign 
Affairs on Friday [24 June] said that the government has no 
concrete plans to set up a representative office in India. 
  Foreign Ministry Spokesman Rock Leng made the statement in 
response to press queries on the possibility of a breakthrough 
in Taiwan's relationship with India. The two nations have had 
no formal contacts since India recognized Beijing in 1949. 
  Commenting on remarks by visiting former Indian Ambassador 
to 
Beijing A.P. Venkateswara that India will establish an office in 
Taipei by the end of August, Leng said that his ministry needs 
to verify that Venkateswara's remarks reflect the policy of the 
Indian Government. He said that the government hopes to develop 
relations with India, but that developing a relationship would 
take time. 
  Venkateswara, a member of an Indian delegation that arrived 
here last Friday, met with Vice Foreign Minister Fang Chin-yen 
on earlier this week, Other members of the Indian delegation 
include former Foreign Minister I.K. Gujral and the former 
Governor of India's central Bank, R.N. Malhotra. 
  While meeting Gujral Friday morning, President Li Teng-hui 
said that he hoped Gujral's visit would help restart exchanges 
between the two nations. 

</TEXT>

