<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Urges Cut in Japanese Imports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Urges Cut in Japanese Imports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2406133594 Taipei CNA in English 1308 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2406133594 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Lilian Wu] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, June 24 (CNA) -- The Ministry of Economic 
Affairs on Friday [24 June] urged Taiwan business people to cut 
imports of Japanese consumer goods to help trim Taiwan's huge 
trade deficit with that country. Taiwan's trade deficit with 
Japan hit a record U.S.$14.42 billion in 1993, and the deficit 
is expected to top U.S.$15 billion this year. 
  A ministry official urged Taiwan importers to diversify 
their 
sources of imports and to help promote domestic-made goods they 
would normally buy from Japan. Ministry statistics show that 
increasing salaries here combined with fewer import restrictions 
and the popularity of Japanese goods have worked to boost 
Japanese imports year after year. Last year, 34 types of 
Japanese goods were imported to the tune of U.S.$10 million each 
-- mostly electrical appliances, food additives, hygiene and 
beauty products, film, and video games. 
  The ministry official said a field study of Japanese imports 
found that products that are no longer popular in Japan may 
still sell in Taiwan for more than two or three times the cost 
of similar Taiwan products. He said some domestic importers 
even import Japanese foodstuffs whose "use-by" dates have 
expired, banking on their popularity here to turn a brisk profit. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

