<F P=100> Northeast Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Measures Taken To Keep Liaoning Reservoir Clean </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Measures Taken To Keep Liaoning Reservoir Clean </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2506022594 Beijing XINHUA in English 0204 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2506022594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shenyang, June 25 (XINHUA) -- The water of a major 
reservoir in northeast China's Liaoning Province is becoming 
cleaner thanks to the local government's continuous efforts for 
water resources protection over the past few years. 
  According to a water resources management official, the 
latest survey shows that the reservoir meets the national 
standards for drinking water and its transparency is increasing. 
  The Dahuofang Reservoir, covering an area of 5,437 sq km and 
with a water storage capacity of 2.187 billion cu m, is one of 
the country's biggest and provides drinking water for millions 
of urban dwellers in Fushun and Shenyang cities, as well as 
water for industrial use. 
  To protect the water resources in the reservoir, the 
provincial government formulated a special regulation as early 
as in 1990 to shut down all industrial enterprises that could 
cause pollution in the area of the reservoir. 
  Other steps taken to keep the water from pollution were a 
ban 
on swimming and sports in and around the reservoir and the 
removal of several poultry and pig farms. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

