<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Guangdong Governor Gives Briefing on Flood Situation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Guangdong Governor Gives Briefing on Flood Situation </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    30,000 Rail Passengers Stranded </H4>

<F P=102> OW2406144194 Beijing XINHUA in English 1426 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2406144194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Guangzhou, June 24 (XINHUA) -- About 30,000 
passengers have been held up in this provincial capital of 
Guangdong because of serious flooding which hit six southern 
Chinese provinces from the middle of this month. 
  According to officials with the Guangzhou Railway 
Administration, by this morning, the station had cancelled 44 
passenger trains to other cities across the country since June 
15, when it first stopped operating the No. 142 passenger train 
to Chongqing city, Sichuan Province. 
  Some 100,000 passengers' trips in all were affected by the 
cancellations. 
  The officials said they had to cancel more passenger trains 
to Tianjin, Hangzhou and Kunming today and tomorrow. Almost all 
the passenger trains now starting from Guangzhou going 
southwards have arrived later than scheduled. 
  They predicted that train services at the station would not 
be fully back to normal for several days. 
  For the past week the station has been staffing three extra 
counters round the clock to deal with returned train tickets. 
  The number of passengers using the local civil air service 
also plunged sharply compared with normal times. Many groups 
who had planned to travel here for sightseeing or business 
returned their air tickets and cancelled their plans. 
  But officials with the Guangzhou Baiyun Airport of China 
South Airlines said that, in the past several days, the number 
of air passengers seemed to be climbing again, as more and more 
people switched to air travel from rail. 
  Water transport from Guangzhou to other areas was also 
forced 
to stop, until the water route from Guangzhou to Huizhou resumed 
the day before yesterday. 
  The flooding on the Beijiang and Xijiang rivers has driven 
the water level in the Pearl (Zhujiang) River up swiftly, 
causing some areas of Guangzhou to be flooded and affecting 
local transport. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

