<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS$ </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Praises Suzhou Industrial Park in Jiangsu </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Praises Suzhou Industrial Park in Jiangsu </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2506133694 Beijing XINHUA in English 1307 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2506133694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Roundup: Suzhou Industrial Park Expected To Blaze Trail in </F>
China's Market Economy"] 
  [Text] Nanjing, June 25 (XINHUA) -- Suzhou -- known as the 
"Oriental Venice" -- in east China's Jiangsu Province, is bound 
to blaze a trail in China's switch to a market economy if it 
makes a success of setting up a Sino-Singapore industrial park. 
  The project, scheduled for completion early next century, is 
the country's current biggest foreign cooperative item. 
  "This is a new mode of cooperation between two governments, 
which has never been seen before," said Chinese Vice-Premier Li 
Lanqing during a recent tour of the city. 
  "It is a strategic step, rather than a commercial measure," 
he said. 
  The establishment of special economic zones, open coastal 
cities, economic and technology development zones in the coastal 
areas and the opening up of border trade have greatly 
facilitated China's economic development and opening further to 
the outside world. 
  But China is not resting on its laurels. 
  In November last year, when Jiang Zemin, Chinese president 
and general secretary of the Chinese Communist Party, met with 
Singaporean Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong at Seattle, in the 
United States, Jiang said that the Chinese Government regarded 
Singapore's experience in developing its country as important, 
and valued Sino-Singapore cooperation. 
  He highly commended the joint efforts to build and develop 
the Suzhou industrial park, which "will create a new mode in 
Sino- Singapore cooperation." 
  Zhang Xinsheng, mayor of Suzhou, said the project is 
characterized by drawing a great deal of international capital 
and Singapore's experience in combining economic operation with 
public administration. 
  "Construction of the Suzhou industrial park will be in line 
with Singapore's experience in urban planning, management and 
social insurance," Zhang said. 
  So far, the two countries have set up a joint development 
company to take charge of the development of the project, open 
bidding and to raise funds. 
  The two governments have set up the Suzhou Industrial Park 
Joint Coordinating Council, chaired by Chinese Vice-Premier Li 
Lanqing and Singapore Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong. 
  The council, which has two working committees, is 
responsible 
for major issues regarding the park. 
  According to the agreement concluded by the two governments, 
the Suzhou Industrial Park Administrative Committee will play an 
independent operational role in line with Chinese law and 
regulations and the requirements of the socialist market economy. 
  These organizations are now operating smoothly. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-26732 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi123_o_94004" </HT>


