<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS$ </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shanghai To Produce TV Series on Jewish Refugees </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shanghai To Produce TV Series on Jewish Refugees </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2506132394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1310 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2506132394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, June 25 (XINHUA) -- Shanghai is to make a 
TV series recalling the city's humanitarianism towards European 
Jews trying to escape from Hitler's holocaust in the years 
before and during the second world war. 
  The history series is to be called "Shanghai Ark." It will 
show how Shanghai people helped the Jews and sheltered them 
while many other countries and ports refused to accept the 
Jewish refugees. 
  About 10,000 Jewish refugees from European countries came to 
Shanghai from 1933 to 1941. Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhaq 
Rabin said in a visit to Shanghai in 1993 that when the Jews 
were being killed by the Nazi regime and forced to leave home 
and wander about, the Shanghai people gave refuge to them. 
Rabin expressed gratitude to the people of Shanghai. 
  The TV series is expected to be shown at the end of the 
year. 
It will be dedicated to the commemoration of the 50th 
anniversary of the end of World War II. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-26736 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi123_o_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-123 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS$ </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Unified Securities Market Taking Shape in Shanghai </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Unified Securities Market Taking Shape in Shanghai </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2406163694 Beijing XINHUA in English 1611 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2406163694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, June 24 (XINHUA) -- A spokesman for the 
Shanghai Securities Exchange announced here today that the 
securities exchange has succeeded in doing on-line business 
linked with 12 other securities exchange centers throughout 
China. 
  At a news briefing, the spokesman said that this has not 
only 
provided investors in various parts of the country with easy 
ways of selling and buying the securities listed at the Shanghai 
Securities Exchange, but also greatly raised the efficiency of 
the securities market and indicated that a unified securities 
market has taken shape in China. 
  The spokesman said that after succeeding in doing on-line 
business with securities exchange centers in Fujian, Shenyang, 
Sichuan, Hainan, Qingdao, Hunan and Guangzhou, the Shanghai 
Securities Exchange has recently gone on-line with securities 
exchange centers in Anhui, Harbin and Beijing. 
  It has also been one-way linked with the staq [as received] 
legal-person stock exchange system. 
  It is planned that representatives of the Shanghai 
Securities 
Exchange will attend a meeting in Hangzhou on June 28 and 29 
together with representatives from other exchange centers 
throughout China to discuss how to further promote the on-line 
work and develop a unified securities market. 

</TEXT>

