<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Standardization of Company Listings Issued </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Standardization of Company Listings Issued </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK2606050694 Beijing CHINA DAILY in English 26 Jun 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> HK2606050694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing CHINA DAILY </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Ren Kan: "Securities Traders Get Information Yardstick"] </F>
  [Text] Current and prospective players on the securities 
market received a boost yesterday when the China Securities 
Regulatory Commission (CSRC) issued regulations concerning the 
required formats of interim reports published by listed 
companies. 
  The stipulations aim to present information concerning the 
structure, management and performance of the listed companies in 
a more standardized format. This should allow investors to 
compare listed companies, in terms of an investment risk, more 
readily. 
  Analysts said that the move will also revitalize 
international investors' enthusiasm for buying Chinese shares. 
  Sufficient information will help them better understand 
Chinese firms and make right investment decision. 
  According to the format, the interim report should include a 
financial report, review and forecast of business operation, 
company's major events, changes of the company's stock 
structure, brief introduction of provisional general meeting and 
documents for future reference. 
  The CSRC requires that the board directors of each company 
should guarantee the accuracy, truth and fairness of the reports. 
  The documents should be completed within 60 days after the 
end of the first six months of the fiscal year. 
  The listed companies should submit 10 copies of their 
reports 
to the CSRC and stock exchanges for record purposes. 
  These reports will be issued in at least one of the eight 
domestic newspapers and magazines which are authorized by CSRC 
to issue securities information. 
  They include, China Daily, Financial News, Economic Daily, 
China Securities, Securities Market Weekly, Shanghai Securities 
News, Securities Times and China Reform Newspaper. 
  Chinese companies, which list their shares on both domestic 
and overseas exchanges, should issue their interim reports at 
the same time to domestic and overseas investors. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

