<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Record' Loans Set for Grain, Cotton Producing Areas </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Record' Loans Set for Grain, Cotton Producing Areas </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2606013594 Beijing XINHUA in English 0120 GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2606013594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 26 (XINHUA) -- The Chinese Government 
has decided to arrange record-breaking preferential loans -- 6.5 
billion yuan in all -- to 523 big grain producing and 150 big 
cotton producing counties annually for five years, starting this 
year. 
  Liang Tiangeng, an official of the Ministry of Agriculture, 
said that the counties, selected by the central government from 
among over 2,000 counties across the country, are in 29 
provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions. 
  "Such an amount of loans for agriculture is really 
unprecedented," Liang said in an interview with XINHUA. 
  The move was designed as part of the efforts to boost the 
country's grain and cotton production. The selection was made 
mainly according to the total annual output of their grain and 
cotton, the official said. 
  The annual loan for the 523 counties totals five billion 
yuan 
(574 million U.S. dollars), while the 150 cotton producing 
counties will be given 1.5 billion yuan (nearly 200 million U.S. 
dollars) of loans each year. 
  The annual interest rate for the loans will be eight 
percent, 
a discount of about two percent, he said. 
  The actual loans for each of the 673 counties will be linked 
to the amount of grain and cotton they produce and sell to the 
state. 
  The provinces, cities and counties involved are themselves 
required to finance 20-30 percent of the total investment needed 
for the programs. 
  The official said that the 673 counties are also required to 
ensure a stable increase in grain and cotton output and sell the 
amount of grain and cotton set by the governments. 
  The 673 counties are encouraged by the central government to 
develop a diversified rural economy, including production of 
high-yielding and profitable farm produce, livestock and aquatic 
products, after they have produced the set amount of grain and 
cotton. 
  East China's Jiangsu Province holds 60 of the 673 counties, 
followed by the country's other leading grain and cotton 
producers -- the Provinces of Shandong, Henan, Anhui, Hubei, 
Heilongjiang, Sichuan and Hebei. 
  One hundred and twelve of the 150 cotton-producing counties 
are in Shandong, Henan, Hubei or Jiangsu Provinces and Xinjiang 
Uygur Autonomous Region. 
  In another development, the central government has also 
earmarked one billion yuan (114 million U.S. dollars) for loans 
each year for five years to support the development of 
high-yielding and better farm produce across the country. 
  The central government's aim with those loans is to make 
efficient use of resources and increase farmers' incomes, as 
China is in the process of adopting a socialist market economy 
and the demand for better farm produce is on the increase. 
  The plan is for about 30 demonstration areas for such farm 
produce to be chosen, about one for each of the 30 provinces, 
municipalities or autonomous regions, and several big cities 
such as Chongqing in Sichuan Province and Qingdao in Shandong 
Province. 
  The demonstration areas will be of different types, such as 
export-oriented agriculture areas, hi-tech or ecological ones, 
and will serve as examples for farmers elsewhere. 
  Experts say that the move, together with a package of other 
agriculture-related steps this year by the government, such as 
the raising of grain and cotton prices, will make grain and 
cotton production much more profitable for farmers, particularly 
in the leading grain and cotton producing areas. 
  Analysts believe that all these moves will boost grain and 
cotton production and increase farmers' incomes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

