<H3> <TI>   Dissident Li Guiren Released From Prison in Xian </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dissident Li Guiren Released From Prison in Xian </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK2606043294 Hong Kong AFP in English 0411 GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> HK2606043294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 26 (AFP) -- Chinese dissident Li 
Guiren has been released from prison after serving a sentence 
for his role in the 1989 pro-democracy movement, friends said 
Sunday. Li, 51, was released Saturday from his prison in the 
central city of Xian. The sources said he was weak and in poor 
health. 
  The former journalist was arrested June 26, 1989. He was 
sentenced to five years jail for "anti-revolutionary propaganda" 
in February 1991. The dissident had organised a strike at the 
Xian publishing house where he was chief editor and openly 
supported deposed Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang during the 
pro-democracy demonstrations that were brutally suppressed in 
1989. He was freed on parole in February 1993 for medical 
treatment after suffering severe heart problems but continued 
his pro-democracy activities and was imprisoned again in 
February of this year. 
  Li's family said he was refused proper treatment while in 
hospital. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

