<F P=100> West Europe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Portuguese Foreign Minister Views Ties With Beijing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Portuguese Foreign Minister Views Ties With Beijing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2506172794 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0535 
GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2506172794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporter Chen Jiaying (7115 1367 3841)] </F>
  [Text] Lisbon, 21 Jun (XINHUA) -- Portuguese Foreign 
Affairs Minister Durao Barroso pointed out in Lisbon on 21 June: 
Portugal and China are comprehensively developing friendly and 
cooperative relations in the political, economic, and cultural 
fields. 
  While meeting and feting outgoing Chinese Ambassador to 
Portugal Wu Tao, Foreign Minister Barroso said: After 
establishing diplomatic relations in 1979, particularly after 
the Portuguese and Chinese Governments signed a joint communique 
on the Macao issue in 1987, the two countries have been 
enhancing bilateral relations in an all-around manner. 
  Barroso said: Portugal and China have different national 
conditions and systems. However, their ways of resolving 
problems left over by history and of handling relations between 
the two countries can be termed exemplary. He expressed the 
hope that Portugal and China will further enhance bilateral 
relations and will continually make contributions to advancing 
the common interests of the Portuguese and Chinese people and to 
facilitating global peace and prosperity. 
  The Portuguese foreign minister also pointed out: At 
present, the Portuguese and Chinese Governments are making joint 
efforts to facilitate a smooth transfer of Macao. Macao has 
become a link for the two countries to enhance bilateral 
relations. Portugal and China will still continue to maintain 
friendly relations for generations after 1999. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

