<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Japanese Diet To Vote on No-Confidence Motion </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Japanese Diet To Vote on No-Confidence Motion </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2406170894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1545 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2406170894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 24 (XINHUA) -- Japan's ruling coalition 
and the opposition agreed tonight to convene a plenary session 
of the House of Representatives early tommorrow morning to vote 
on a no-confidence motion against the minority government of 
Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata, the KYODO NEWS SERVICE reported. 
  According to party officials, they reached the agreement at 
a 
meeting of directors of the lower house's steering committee. 
  If Hata fails to survive the no-confidence motion introduced 
by the leading opposition liberal party, he must either resign 
with his entire cabinet or dissolve the lower house for a snap 
election. 
  Talks between leaders of the ruling coalition and the second 
largest opposition Social Democratic Party (SDP) [Social 
Democratic Party of Japan -- SDPJ] are now under way, but 
prospects seem to be dim for an agreement on a future 
re-alliance. 
  If the coalition's efforts fail to entice the SDP back into 
the governing camp, the SDP may support the no-confidence 
motion, which means it would be readily approved in the lower 
chamber. 
  The SDP and the ruling coalition remain at odds over the 
resignation of Hata and the formation of a new government. 
  The ruling coalition has rejected demands from the SDP that 
Hata and his cabinet resign en masse, the principle condition 
set by the SDP for returning to the fold. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

