<H3> <TI>   Japanese Envoy Announces Aid to Flood-Stricken Areas </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Japanese Envoy Announces Aid to Flood-Stricken Areas </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2406134794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1320 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2406134794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 24 (XINHUA) -- The Japanese 
Government is giving a million U.S. dollars worth of urgent aid 
to help south China's six provinces suffering from the effects 
of flood disasters. 
  Koichi Matsumoto, charge d'affaires ad interim of the 
Japanese Embassy in Beijing, announced his government's decision 
to give the emergency aid when he met here today with Long 
Yongtu, Chinese assistant minister of foreign trade and economic 
cooperation. 
  The aid will include 800,000 U.S. dollars, and 100 small 
generators worth 200,000 U.S. dollars. 
  Matsumoto said that the Japanese Government made the 
decision 
out of humanitarian considerations, since the scale of the 
disaster was very large, and Japan-China ties are very good. 
  In the past two weeks, rainstorms and floods have hit 
southern China's provinces of Guangdong, Hubei, Jiangxi, 
Zhejiang and Fujian as well as the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous 
Region. 

</TEXT>

