<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shanghai-Nagasaki Shipping Line Reopened </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shanghai-Nagasaki Shipping Line Reopened </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2506165394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1546 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2506165394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, June 25 (XINHUA) -- A direct shipping line 
between Shanghai and Nagasaki in Japan was fully restored today 
after a suspension of 52 years. 
  The return here today of the vessel "Haihua" from a six-day 
round trip to Nagasaki completed the first direct sea link 
between the two cities since 1942. 
  Nagasaki, only 462 miles away, is the nearest Japanese sea 
port for Shanghai. There used to be a shipping line between the 
two cities. It was suspended in 1942. 
  In order to promote exchanges between the two port cities, 
Nagasaki County government proposed in 1988 to resume the 
shipping line. Through efforts by both of governmental and 
non-governmental organizations of the two cities, the shipping 
line was finally opened. 
  Yang Zhengding, general manager of the Shanghai-Nagasaki 
INternational Ferry Co. Ltd., said that the reopening of the 
route reflects the common will of the people in the two cities 
and the needs of economic development of the two cities. 

</TEXT>

