<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Li Peng Pledges Beijing Ready To Work for G-77 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Li Peng Pledges Beijing Ready To Work for G-77 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2506055694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0532 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2506055694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] United Nations, June 24 (XINHUA) -- The Group of 77, 
the largest organization of developing countries, marked the 
30th anniversary of its establishment at a special ministerial 
meeting here today. 
  The group enlarged its membership to 130 today by admitting 
South Africa as a new member. 
  Created on June 15, 1964 by 77 developing countries, the 
group has played a cardinal role in international economic 
relations, calling for the establishment of a new international 
economic order, safeguarding the legitimate rights and interests 
of developing countries, and working as a major actor in 
promoting development and international economic cooperation. 
  Presiding over the meeting, Algerian Foreign Minister 
Mohamed 
Salah Dembri, who is chairman of the Group of 77, said the group 
faced the challenge of further strengthening its role, so that, 
30 years after its founding, its common ideals might live on and 
the complementary interests of all the members might be 
effectively promoted. 
  The group should maintain its cohesion, broaden its horizon 
and reaffirm its originality, specificity and independence, he 
said. 
  UN Secretary-General Butrus Butrus-Ghali praised the group's 
efforts for developing countries to gain independence and 
promote development. 
  "Long indeed has been the road traveled by this group toward 
what is today the underpinning of United Nations action for 
development," he said. 
  UN General Assembly President S.R. Insanally congratulated 
the group on its "splendid record of achievement" and said he 
believed the group, through their collective efforts, would 
"continue to make progress toward the goal of full development 
for all peoples." 
  Chinese Premier Li Peng sent a telegram to the special 
meeting, extending China's warm congratulations to the group and 
pledging that China stands "ready to work with the Group of 77 
for a gradual reform of the international economic order and for 
the common development and prosperity of developing countries." 
  China's permanent representative to the UN Li Zhaoxing told 
the meeting that China has decided to contribute 10,000 U.S. 
dollars to the group. 
  At today's meeting, representatives from the group's member 
states reaffirmed their commitment to strengthening south-south 
cooperation, called for renewing the dialogue between the north 
and the south, and urged developed countries to implement their 
commitments to international economic cooperation, providing 
developing countries with financial and technological support. 
  The meeting adopted a ministerial declaration which put 
forward a new strategy of action of developing countries for the 
year 2000 and beyond in light of the current world situation, 
and a ministerial statement on "an agenda for development." 
  It also adopted terms of reference of the joint coordinating 
committee between the Group of 77 and the Non-Aligned Movement, 
another grouping of developing countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

