<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Chooses Delegates for Korean Presummit Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Chooses Delegates for Korean Presummit Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2506162194 Beijing XINHUA in English 1444 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2506162194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, June 25 (XINHUA) -- Kim Yong-sun was 
named today as the leader of the Democratic People's Republic of 
Korea's (DPRK) delegation to the forthcoming pre-Korean summit 
talks at the truce village of Panmunjom. 
  Kim, chairman of the Reunification Policy Committee of the 
Supreme People's Assembly, will be accompanied at the June 28 
meeting by An Pyong-su, vice-chairman of the committee for the 
Peaceful Reunification of the Fatherland, and Paek Nam-chun, 
chief councillor of the DPRK Administration Council (cabinet). 
  Details of the delegation membership were given to South 
Korean Premier Yi Yong-tok by the DPRK Prime Minister Kang 
Song-san today. 
  The meeting was proposed by Kang on June 20 as a means of 
organizing detailed arrangements for a North-South summit. The 
DPRK accepted the proposal two days later. 
  Meanwhile, a DPRK Foreign Ministry spokesman said the 
outstanding questions between the DPRK and the U.S., including 
the nuclear issue of the Korean peninsula and other issues, 
could be resolved in a package deal at the third-round DPRK-U.S. 
talks. 
  Officials from the two countries will meet in Geneva in the 
first week of July for talks over a wide range of political and 
economic issues. 
  However, the spokesman also criticized Japan and South Korea 
following their public outcry calling for a "special inspection" 
of the DPRK's military facilities. 

</TEXT>

